<HL> LEISURE &amp; ARTS: Time Off: Diversions and Excursions Oct. 4-17 </HL>
<SO> </SO>
<TEXT>
      ART
   National Museum of Natural History, Smithsonian Institution, Washington, D.C.: "Crossroads of Continents: Cultures of Siberia and Alaska" -- The first joint Soviet-North American exhibit ever organized explores the history, art and traditional cultures of the native peoples on both sides of the Bering Strait, from Siberia to British Columbia. 
The nearly 600 artifacts -- from kayaks and harpoons to masks, drums and weapons of war -- date from 20,000 years ago to the present. 
One-third of the works come from Leningrad's Museum of Anthropology and Ethnography. 10th Street and Constitution Avenue, through April 2, 1989. 
The show then moves to the Museum of History and Industry at the Seattle Center, Seattle (May 14-Oct. 15, 1989); the American Museum of Natural History, Manhattan (Nov. 26, 1989-March 25, 1990); and the Indiana State Museum, Indianapolis (May 6-Sept. 9. 1990). 
Additional North American venues through January 1992, followed by a two-year tour of four Soviet cities. 

   Fogg Art Museum, Cambridge, Mass.: "A Prosperous Past: The Sumptuous Still Life in the Netherlands 1600-1700" -- More than 50 17th-century Dutch still-life paintings by such masters of the genre as Willem Kalf, Abraham van Beyeren and Pieter Claesz. 
The show documents the emergence of still life (the English word comes from the Dutch, stilleven) as an independent type of painting during the "golden age" of Rembrandt, Vermeer and Hals. 32 Quincy St. (on the Harvard campus), through Nov. 27. 
The exhibit travels to the Kimbell Art Museum, Fort Worth, Texas, Dec. 10, 1988-Jan. 29, 1989. 

   Colorado Springs Fine Arts Center, Colorado Springs, Colo.: "Art of Sport: Selections From the National Art Museum of Sport" -- More than 60 paintings and sculptures from the nation's foremost museum of sport art, based in West Haven, Conn. 
Sports depicted range from basketball and boxing to skating, luge and bicycle racing. 
Also on view are medals, posters, sporting equipment and other Olympic memorabilia from the U.S. Olympic Committee Archives. 30 West Dale, through Oct. 30. 

   POETRY
   International Poetry Forum, Pittsburgh, salutes T.S. Eliot's centenary. 
British poetry readers Jill Balcon and Gabriel Woolf present selections of Eliot's poetry plus a scene from his play "The Cocktail Party" on Oct. 5; and poets Louis Simpson, Rosanna Warren and Theodore Weiss offer "A Poetic Tribute to T.S. Eliot" on Oct. 10. 
Both at Carnegie Lecture Hall. 
Also on the 10th, there's a T.S. Eliot symposium at Music School Recital Hall, Duquesne University. (412) 621-9893. 

   DANCE
   Martha Graham Dance Company: Tonight at City Center, where this troupe kicks off a three-week Manhattan season, the audience will be seeing stars: Mikhail Baryshnikov, Kathleen Turner and Maya Plisetskaya. 
At the opening gala, Mr. B dances the Penitent in "El Penitente" for the first time, Ms. T. essays the role of "She Who Speaks" for the first time, and Ms. P performs "The Dying Swan" for the umpteenth time. 
Highlights of the rest of the engagement include the world premiere of Ms. Graham's 178th work, to traditional Navajo music, on Oct. 13; "Fragments," a series of excerpts from Graham classics; and the revival of the erotic "Phaedra." 131 West 55th St. Through Oct. 23. 

   MUSIC
   Chicago Lyric Opera: The medieval minstrel Tannhauser is a TV evangelist in a new production of the Wagner epic staged by -- who else? -- Peter Sellars. 
Richard Cassilly takes on the title role; Nadine Secunde sings the redemptive Elisabeth. 
Ferdinand Leitner conducts. 
Oct. 10. 14, 18, 22, 26, 31, Nov. 5. (312) 332-2244. 

   Minnesota Orchestra, conducted by Edo de Waart in his third season as music director, offers Bruckner's Symphony No. 5, B-flat major (Oct. 5, 7, 8). 
The orchestra will be joined Oct. 12-15 by soprano Arleen Auger. 
The evening's entertainment: Stravinsky's "Le Chant du Rossignol," Canteloube's "Songs of the Auvergne," Ravel's "Sheherazade," and Mussorgsky/Ravel's "Pictures at an Exhibition." 
Minneapolis's Orchestra Hall (1111 Nicollet Mall) and Ordway Music Theatre (345 Washington St.). (612) 371-5656. 

   Prince: The steamy showman bumps and grinds his way across North America with his theatrically staged "Lovesexy" spectacle. 
The concert promises a regulation-sized basketball court, a hydraulic bed and a lot of hot funk -- Toronto (Maple Leaf Garden), Oct. 5; Hampton, Va. (Coliseum), Oct. 8; Landover, Md. (Capitol Center), Oct. 10-11; Atlanta (Omni), Oct. 13-14; Greensboro, N.C. (Coliseum), Oct. 16; Philadelphia (Spectrum), Oct. 18; Worcester, Mass. (Centrum), Oct. 20-22; Uniondale, N.Y. (Nassau Coliseum), Oct. 24; Pittsburgh (Civic Arena), Oct. 28; Detroit (Joe Louis Arena), Oct. 30-31; Los Angeles (Sports Arena), Nov. 5-8; Oakland, Calif. (Coliseum), Nov. 10-12. 

